sets

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict sets with age, gender, marital, education, family_income, number_volunteer_r and time_point (formula: sets ~ 1 + age + gender + marital + education + family_income + number_volunteer_r + time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.29) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.28. The model’s intercept, corresponding to age = 0, gender = female, marital = divorced, education = secondary, family_income = 0_10000, number_volunteer_r = 0 and time_point = 1st , is at 21.63 (S.E. = 2.88, p < .001, 95% CI [15.99, 27.26]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.02, S.E. = 0.03, p = 0.446, 95% CI [-0.08, 0.04]; Std. beta = -0.17, 95% CI [-0.61, 0.27])
  • The effect of gender [male] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.97, S.E. = 0.98, p = 0.324, 95% CI [-0.96, 2.90]; Std. beta = 0.49, 95% CI [-0.48, 1.47])
  • The effect of marital [married] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -3.00, S.E. = 1.70, p = 0.078, 95% CI [-6.34, 0.33]; Std. beta = -1.52, 95% CI [-3.21, 0.17])
  • The effect of marital [single] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -2.79, S.E. = 1.68, p = 0.097, 95% CI [-6.08, 0.50]; Std. beta = -1.41, 95% CI [-3.07, 0.25])
  • The effect of education [post-secondary] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.82, S.E. = 1.26, p = 0.515, 95% CI [-1.65, 3.30]; Std. beta = 0.42, 95% CI [-0.84, 1.67])
  • The effect of education [university] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.71, S.E. = 0.87, p = 0.416, 95% CI [-1.00, 2.43]; Std. beta = 0.36, 95% CI [-0.51, 1.23])
  • The effect of family income [10001_20000] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.76, S.E. = 1.13, p = 0.503, 95% CI [-1.46, 2.97]; Std. beta = 0.38, 95% CI [-0.74, 1.50])
  • The effect of family income [20001_30000] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -2.02e-03, S.E. = 1.26, p = 0.999, 95% CI [-2.47, 2.47]; Std. beta = -1.02e-03, 95% CI [-1.25, 1.25])
  • The effect of family income [30001_40000] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 1.31, S.E. = 1.16, p = 0.256, 95% CI [-0.95, 3.58]; Std. beta = 0.66, 95% CI [-0.48, 1.81])
  • The effect of family income [40000_above] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.43, S.E. = 1.16, p = 0.708, 95% CI [-2.70, 1.83]; Std. beta = -0.22, 95% CI [-1.37, 0.93])
  • The effect of number volunteer r is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.79, S.E. = 0.40, p = 0.049, 95% CI [3.63e-03, 1.57]; Std. beta = 0.38, 95% CI [1.78e-03, 0.77])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 1.15, S.E. = 0.75, p = 0.125, 95% CI [-0.32, 2.61]; Std. beta = 0.58, 95% CI [-0.16, 1.32])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.

nb_mcs

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict nb_mcs with age, gender, marital, education, family_income, number_volunteer_r and time_point (formula: nb_mcs ~ 1 + age + gender + marital + education + family_income + number_volunteer_r + time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.68) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.30. The model’s intercept, corresponding to age = 0, gender = female, marital = divorced, education = secondary, family_income = 0_10000, number_volunteer_r = 0 and time_point = 1st , is at 48.63 (S.E. = 12.64, p < .001, 95% CI [23.85, 73.41]).
